## Rules

1. **Verbatim.** Copy the criterion exactly as written in the corpus — do not paraphrase, summarize,
   or "improve" it. Paraphrasing loses statutory nuance and breaks traceability.
2. **One row = one testable assertion.** If a corpus sentence bundles several checks, split it into
   several AC rows so each maps to one test. Note the split in the source citation (same `file:line`).
3. **Every AC maps to a verification (opt-in testing, mandatory only for protected core).**
   Protected-core ACs (state machine, RBAC read-scope + gates, audit invariants, snapshot
   immutability, allocation/capacity/temporal/SLA math, scoring, merge resolvers) require a **passing
   automated test against a real DB** — fill `Verification ref` with the test path. Every other AC is
   **verified on the live app** — fill `Verification ref` with `live-app: <route>` (typecheck + lint +
   a real click; no test required). An AC with neither a green protected-core test nor a recorded
   live-app verification is **not done**, regardless of what a sub-agent reports.
4. **Stable ids, append-only.** Never renumber. A withdrawn AC is struck through and annotated, not
   deleted — traceability outlives the requirement.
5. **Surface tag drives the ticket split.** `[backend]`→ B-ticket, `[frontend]`→ F-ticket,
   `[both]`→ both, `[contract]`→ a contracts change the integrator regenerates.
6. **Silence is logged, not invented.** If the corpus is ambiguous about an AC, record the gap in
   `docs/open-questions.md` and capture the conservative default you tested against — don't bake a
   guess into a verbatim row.
